Meteorology of Saint John - Temperature. The mean temperature of May was about 1.5 ° below that of 1864, and nearly a quarter of a degree below the average of 15 years. The highest reading of the thermometer was 67 ° on the 29th, and the or lowest 32 ° on the 8th. On this latter morning ice nearly an eighth of an inch thick, was formed in exposed places in the vicinity of the City. Last year the highest reading of the thermometer in May was 78 ° on the 28th, and the extreme range for the month 35°. The greatest oscillation in one day was 19° (8th) and the average for the month 9.8° -- Last year the maximum oscillation was 27°, and the monthly mean 12.26°. The average of the latter for 5 years is 11.45°.   Looking at the weekly temperatures--the first was 2.7° colder than in 1864, the second 2.83°, and the  third 2.75°, while the fourth was 1.6° warmer. For the various hours of observations the mean readings for this year and last were as follows: ----  1865 [In degrees]  6am: 44.50° 10am: 49.84° 2pm: 52.68° 6pm: 50.10° 10pm: 46.77° --- 1864 [In degrees]  6am: 44.19° 10am: 51.30° 2pm: 55.87° 6pm: 49.55° 10pm: 47.19°
column60: Barometer -- The mean pressure of the atmosphere differed little from that of last year and during the month there was no extreme or violent disturbance. The highest reading of the barometer was 30.374 inch on the 19th, and the lowest 29.480 on the 26th. The extreme range  was thus 0.944 inch, In May '64 the highest reading was 30.3 inch on the 16th, and the lowest 29.322 on the 27th. The greatest mean daily range of pressure was 0.415, between the 9th and 10th, but the monthly average was 0.164 inch. The maximum  of mean daily range in May last year was 0.33 inch, and the average for the month 0.109 inch. This latter for 5 years past is 0.172 inch. The tri-daily pressures for this year and last were as follows, corrected for temperature:  ------- 1865 [In inches]:  8am: 29.880 in. 2pm: 29.854 in. 10pm: 029.892 in. Mean of 5 years: 29.832 in.       -----------     Watery Vapour.-The maximum of watery vapor suspended in the atmosphere was 0.585 inch on the 29th, and the minimum 0.172 in. on the 5th. The lowest relative humidity was 70 per cent on the 19th, and the greatest difference  between the readings of the hygrometric thermometers 7° on the 6th. Last year this latter was 15° , and for the year before 18°. The following are the means of the usual tri-daily readings:  Force of Vapour (inches) 8am: 0.303 in. 2pm: 0.343 in. 10pm: 0.316 in. column61: Wind -- The wind was light for the whole month, and was E. to S.W. 21 days, and W. to N.E. 10 days. The most prevalent was S.W May 1864, [which] had 22 days of Southerly weather, and the average for 16 years is about 21% days.   ---------     Ozone was much more plentiful than in any other of the Spring months, and in this respect agreed with the observations of other years. The highest notation was 9.0, with a fresh N.E. wind during the night of the 3rd. Its day mean was 2.05, and its night 2.7. Last year The former was 1.4, and the latter 2.8.
column62: Precipitation. The most notable meteorologic feature of May was its great and very unusual rain-fall, which surpassed by nearly 100% any corresponding month's record for the last 15  years at least. It began with a drenching ruin, and with brief intermissions continued wet to near its close. The highest month's rain on record (for May) since 1850, is 5.4 inch, and the average for the same period (leaving out this year's) [is] 3.07 inch; but this year the May rain was no less than 10.33 inch. It rained on 12 days and 14 nights. The highest  day rain was 1.1 inch on the 9th, and the night rain 2 inches on the 23rd. The total day rain measured 4.50 inch, and the nights 5.44 inch. On the morning and forenoon of the 7th we were favoured with about an inch-and-a-half of snow [1.5 inches], which yielded, when melted, about 3-tonths of water. At Bass River, Kent County, as much as 8 inches of snow fell at this time.  The relative periodical falls of rain and melted snow were as follows, for this year and last:  1865 [in inches]  1st  week: 1.885 2nd week: 2.570 3rd week: 0.830 4th week: 5.035  1864 [in inches]  1st  week: 0.635 2nd week: 0.300 3rd week: 0.160 4th week: 0.870  -  Once only since 1850 has any month's rain been greater than for May last, and that was in November, 1854, when the rain and melted snow was upwards 14.5 inch. Perhaps a better idea will be formed of the May rainfall, when it is known to have been equal to 6.4 wine gallons  per square foot, or 280,500 gallons for each acre of surface within the city. If the estimation were made by weight, it would be fully 53lbs. per square foot, or 2,314,000lbs. (1033 tons) per acre.
column63: Sky.  During the month 5 mornings were clear, 4 days and 7 nights; and 21 mornings, 23 days and 23 nights were wholly clouded. The mean estimated clouding for 8 a. m. Was 7.7; for 2 p. m., 8.1; and for 10 p. m., 7.6. At the same hours 6 mornings were foggy, 4 days and 9 nights.    -----------      Memoranda. -The aurora was seen on 2 nights, and the coast of Nova Scotia on 4 days. On the 17th there was a short thunder-storm that passed to the southward, east of the city On the same day in May, 1864, there was also a thunder-sturm.

Extraordinary meteor. A meteor of a somewhat strange and extraordinary character was seen from this city about 27 minutes to 11 o'clock [10:33pm] tonight. Notice was first drawn to it by a deep whirring noise, similar to what is heard from a newly projected rocket, and as soon as the eye turned in the direction of this strange sound, a number of small star like specks were observed shooting from a common centre a few degrees south of the zenith.
column60: While the noise continued a thin body of luminous matter was projected northwardly. -- After describing a small part it seemed to be arrested in its progress; but the light remained distinctly visible for at least half an hour after. At first it had a sword like shape and in one or two minutes more that of a huge uptill with its creeping quivering motion.
column61: It wore this later appearance for about 5 minutes (by the watch) flowing all the while with a bright bluish light. Its shape and colour then began to alter -- the latter changing to a dull red and orange and the former to that of a mammoth fish -- the head, the body, the fins, the tail everything in fact minutely and perfectly outlined. The colour however was not consistent, but oscillated and for some minutes paled and deepened by turn.
column62: While retaining this fish-like shape the head and body appeared to be much more dense and luminous than the tail which was attenuated and of a pale bluish colour. In about 15 minutes from the time it was first seen it began to lose its definite power and at last appeared as a luminous patch of auroral matter floating lazily in the air, but at a great height and with a westward motion. The air was clear and dry, and a strong west wind prevailed (4.0) at the time.
column63: The mercury in the thermometer markerd 42 degrees and the mean temperature of the day was 48 degrees. the barometer was unusually low (28.923 inch) and had been so all day. During the evening  a number of small meteors were visible, but at a great  distance and without uniformity of motion.
